“Nonsense characters and radicals” become really interesting once you look at language as a compression and reconstruction system rather than just a dictionary.

In many writing systems — especially logographic or semi-logographic systems like Chinese language — radicals act like:

* semantic hints
* phonetic hints
* structural priors
* compression anchors

A character is often not arbitrary.
It may contain:

* a meaning component
* a sound component
* relational structure

So even an unfamiliar or invented character can feel interpretable if it preserves the statistical geometry of the system.

Your brain (and language models) perform something like:

latent reconstruction from partial symbolic cues.

Example idea:

* water radical → maybe liquid/fluid-related
* fire radical → maybe heat/energy-related
* heart radical → emotion/internal state
* metal radical → tools/materials

Even if the full character is fake, humans may infer approximate semantic territory.

That means:

nonsense can still carry structured probability.

This happens in English too.

Words like:

* “slither”
* “glimmer”
* “crunch”
* “snarl”

contain phonesthetic patterns that imply texture/motion/sensation even before formal definition.

Your nervous system extracts statistical structure from:

* shape
* sound
* relation
* co-occurrence
* morphology

So fake words can feel:

* sharp
* soft
* ancient
* technological
* friendly
* threatening

without prior exposure.

That’s because meaning is partially geometric and relational, not purely symbolic lookup.

This also connects strongly to autoencoders and latent spaces:

* radicals act like compressed semantic features
* characters become compositional embeddings
* language becomes reusable symbolic geometry

You can think of radicals almost like:

semantic basis vectors.

Combine enough of them correctly and the system predicts plausible meaning-space locations.

That’s why generated pseudo-script can sometimes look:

* believable
* sacred
* alien
* technical
* emotionally evocative

even when unreadable.

The structure itself carries priors.

And this becomes extremely important for:

* OCR systems
* language models
* tokenization
* symbolic compression
* invented languages
* meme propagation
* branding/logos
* interface iconography

Because humans do not interpret symbols purely rationally.
We infer through relational pattern matching.

A “nonsense” symbol is rarely truly nonsense if it preserves:

* structural grammar
* statistical familiarity
* relational consistency
* aesthetic priors

The brain tries to complete the latent manifold anyway.